  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A cluster of resting orders at unswept failure swings (equal highs/lows or failure swings) where minimal opposing order flow exists, allowing price to move through quickly with little resistance. These levels lack prominent order blocks or fair value gaps defending them and serve as draw-on-liquidity targets after a confirmed change in state of delivery.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a swing high that reversed without first sweeping a prior swing high (lower high formed), or a swing low that reversed without sweeping a prior swing low (higher low formed) — the unswept extreme is the failure swing.",
    "Confirm the swing high/low was never swept (price never ran through the level) before the reversal.",
    "Look for multiple stacked or equal highs/lows that remain untouched, amplifying the LRL pool.",
    "Align the cluster with session reference points (Asia highs/lows, London highs/lows, midnight open, previous day highs/lows); overlapping levels reinforce the low-resistance nature.",
    "Verify that a change in the state of delivery (close beyond a series of same-direction candles) has occurred before treating the cluster as a target.",
    "Confirm the cluster sits on the same side as the anticipated directional move — bullish setups target stacked highs above price; bearish setups target stacked lows below price.",
    "Observe that when price reaches the cluster it moves through quickly without sustained consolidation or reversal, confirming minimal resistance.",
    "Distinguish LRL from high resistance liquidity (HRL) — LRL is unswept; HRL has been swept and is a stop-loss reference.",
    "Ensure LRL resides on the target side of the market, opposite a recently formed HRL zone.",
    "Cross-timeframe identification: mark failure swings on higher timeframe (HTF), verify penetration characteristics on lower timeframe (LTF)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "LRL serves as the primary profit target or draw-on-liquidity, not a reversal zone. After a market structure shift away from HRL, entries are taken on order blocks, fair value gaps, or mean thresholds, targeting the LRL pool. Use the cluster's near edge as an initial partial target and the far edge as final target when risk-to-reward exceeds 2R. Stops should be placed behind HRL, not behind failure swings. LRL sweep confirms the manipulation phase of the Power of Three.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Targeting LRL before a confirmed change in the state of delivery, resulting in premature entries stopped out by continuation.",
    "Treating an LRL sweep as a reversal signal rather than a continuation/manipulation move.",
    "Confusing a fake change in the state of delivery (temporary reversal that re-runs original lows/highs) with a genuine one.",
    "Confusing LRL with high resistance liquidity (HRL) — once swept, a level becomes HRL, not LRL.",
    "Using a level that price never closed through as a valid invalidation point; it must be swept to form HRL before being trusted as a stop reference.",
    "Trading a reversal directly off a failure swing high/low instead of waiting for price to reach a relevant high/low with clear separation.",
    "Placing stop-losses behind failure swings (LRL side), where they are likely to be swept.",
    "Anticipating a reversal without SMT confirmation after only failure swings have been taken out.",
    "Ignoring whether London reached a relevant higher timeframe PD array; if not, LRL may not be reached until New York session.",
    "Failing to identify failure swing conditions correctly: must be adjacent trading days with higher high/lower low on each side.",
    "Using LRL as entry point rather than target or confirmation signal.",
    "Confusing LRL with order blocks: LRL lacks order clustering; order blocks are clear support/resistance.",
    "Identifying LRL on only one timeframe; should use HTF for identification and LTF for penetration verification.",
    "Assuming LRL will be swept without confirmation of market structure shift or CSD.",
    "Treating any historical swing point as LRL without checking if it has been swept.",
    "Not considering economic calendar, session times, and market structure shift when anticipating LRL sweep."
  ],
